os. chdir(path)

In [3]:
#Drop unrelated columns
df = df.drop('film_code',axis='columns')
df = df.drop('cinema_code',axis='columns')
df = df.drop('date',axis='columns')
df = df.drop('month',axis='columns')
df = df.drop('quarter',axis='columns')
df = df.drop('day',axis='columns')

Linear Regression¶

For tickets_sold & total_sales linear regression¶

In [14]:
#Define the dependent and independent variables
x1 = df[['tickets_sold']]
y1 = df['total_sales']
x1_train,x1_test,y1_train,y1_test=train_test_split(x1,y1,test_size=0.3,random_state=30)
In [15]:
# Create linear regression object
reg = linear_model.LinearRegression()
reg.fit(x1_train,y1_train)
Out[15]:
LinearRegression()
In a Jupyter environment, please rerun this cell to show the HTML representation or trust the notebook.
On GitHub, the HTML representation is unable to render, please try loading this page with nbviewer.org.
LinearRegression()
In [16]:
#Prediction
y1_pred = reg.predict(x1_test)
In [17]:
#Fit the sacatter plot with the best line
plt.scatter(x1, y1, color="blue", label="original")
plt.xlabel('tickets_sold')
plt.ylabel('total_sales')
plt.plot(x1_test, y1_pred, color="red", label="predicted")
plt.legend()
plt.show()
In [18]:
#Perfermance measurement
mae_tickets_sold = metrics.mean_absolute_error(y1_test, y1_pred)
mse_tickets_sold = metrics.mean_squared_error(y1_test, y1_pred)
rmse_tickets_sold = np.sqrt(mse_tickets_sold) # or mse**(0.5)
r2_tickets_sold = metrics.r2_score(y1_test,y1_pred)
print("Results of sklearn.metrics:")
print("MAE:",mae_tickets_sold)
print("MSE:", mse_tickets_sold)
print("RMSE:", rmse_tickets_sold)
print("R-Squared:", r2_tickets_sold)

x10 = df[['tickets_out']]

In [61]:
# Create non-linear regression object. We play around with the weighted K-nn to train our model. 

n_neighbors = 5

for i, weights in enumerate(["uniform", "distance"]):
    knn = neighbors.KNeighborsRegressor(n_neighbors, weights=weights)
    knn.fit(x10_train, y10_train)
    y10_pred = knn.predict(x10_test)

    #do the plotting for housing_median age vc housing value. 
    #You may do the scatter plot for other features or try to implement a different visualization.
    plt.subplot(2, 1, i + 1)
    plt.scatter(x10_train, y10_train, color="darkorange", label="data")
    plt.plot(x10_test, y10_pred, color="navy", label="prediction")
    plt.axis("tight")
    plt.legend()
    plt.title("KNeighborsRegressor (k = %i, weights = '%s')" % (n_neighbors, weights))

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()
In [62]:
